<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-152-173 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 798 693</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 20 1991 v8 n20 p157(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Intel forms three groups to bolster marketing. (Intel Corp.) (NewsDigest)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brennan, Laura.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Strategic PlanningOrganization StructureSemiconductor industryReorganizationMarketing Strategy.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Intel Forms Three GroupsandM;To Bolster MarketingandM;Intel Corp. stepped up its counteroffensive against the Advanced ComputingEnvironment last week, creating three new groups to strengthen its marketing.andM;The new Architecture and Applications Group (AAG), Software Technology Group(STG) and Multimedia and Supercomputing Components Group emerged just in timeto keep attention focused on the microprocessor giant's X86 platform,analysts said.andM;&quot;The reorganization is as much for marketing as anything else,&quot; said AndrewKessler, a vice president at investment firm Morgan Stanley andamp; Co., in NewYork.andP;  &quot;They're trying to enhance the external view of what Intel is doing.&quot;andM;The move comes on the heels of Senior Vice President David House'scross-country jaunt this month to promote Intel's alternative to ACE's RISCproposal.andM;The AAG, led by House, will integrate the needs of OEM customers and endusers in future products, as well as handle marketing and communication.andP;  TheMicrocomputer Components Group, which House previously led, will bedissolved.andM;The STG, headed by Intel Vice President Ron Whittier, will work withindependent software developers as well as Intel's internal software teams toensure the creation of software for Intel's platforms.andM;The STG will be key as Intel tries to compete with RISC platforms, Kesslersaid.andP;  There are very few 386-specific programs; Intel needs to jump-startinterest in multiuser, multiprocessing applications if it is to compete withRISC platforms in the years to come, analysts said.andM;-- Laura BrennanandM;</TEXT></DOC>